EEG Based Classification Methodologies for Autism Spectrum Disorder¶

Introduction¶

Autism spectrum disorder (ASD) is a type of neurodevelopmental disorder with core impairments in the social relationships, communication, imagination, or flexibility of thought and restricted repertoire of activity and interest. Despite so much research being conducted, the exact reason as to why this disorder occurs remain unanswered. Due to the increased cases in children diagnosed with ASD, there is need for further research on this population.At present, clinical diagnosis is mainly based on behavioral scale tests and Childhood Autism Rating Scale. Evaluation results may not be very accurate due to certain limitations.

In this study, an effective autism diagnostic system using electroencephalogram (EEG) signals, which are generated from electrical activity in the brain, provide critical information. EEG recordings have several advantages such as high temporal resolution, simplicity, lower costs and wider availability and are shown to be a powerful tool for the study of complex neuropyschiatric disorders.

Research Objective - To classify autistic subjects from normal individuals using machine learning supervised classification methodologies.

Data Description - The resting state eeg data used in this study is collected from Healthy Brain Network(HBN) biobank. The dataset used in this study consists of eeg recordings of 100 autistic subjects and 88 Normal subjects within the same age group between 5-19 years old and 82.8% of the subjects were male and 17.2% were female. The eeg was recorded with HydroCel Geodesic Sensor Net with 128 electrodes + Cz at a sampling rate of 500Hz.

Data Preprocessing :

  • Data preprocessing was performed using mne and braindecode libraries.
  • The Original EEG data were re-referenced with average signal from left and right mastoid sensors as they recorded less signal from the brain.
  • Band-pass filters were applied to restrict the signal to a frequency range of interest between 1-40 Hz
  • To improve computing speed, EEG data were down-sampled to 250 Hz
  • Eyes closed part of the EEG signal were extracted as we focused on analysis with resting state EEG
  • Data was segmented into 20s trails
  • Voltage readings were converted into millivolts for numerical stability
  • Exponential running standardisation was performed to get the standardised data
  • Data obtained is of the shape (n_trails n_channels n_timesteps)

Feature Engineering :

  • Power Spectrum Analysis was perfomed on the segmented trails. The relative power was calculated among the frequency bands :
    • delta (0-4 Hz)
    • theta (4-8 Hz)
    • alpha (8-12 Hz)
    • beta (13-30 Hz)
  • Relative power is the ratio of each frequency's band power to the total power. The purpose of calculating the relative power is to explore abnormalities in the fluctations of autistic EEG compared with normal.
  • Extracted features were stored in dataframe with 440 features (110 channels * 4 features)

Feature Selection using PCA :

  • Irravelent or partially relevant features could negatively impact on the performance of the model. By performing feature selection we would-
    • Reduce Overfitting
    • Improve Accuracy
    • Reduce Training Time
  • PCA is used for denoising and dimensionality reduction
  • PCA for dimensionality reduction means zeroing out one or more smallest prinical components, resulting in lower dimensional projection of data preserving maximum variance. In this study, PCA is performed with 95% variance. Features were reduced to 47

Machine Learning Models :

  • Following classification algorithms have been implemented
    • K-Nearest Neighbors
    • Logistic Regression
    • Decision Trees
    • Random Forest
    • Extra Trees Classifier
    • Xgboost Classifier
  • A Convolution Neural Network with one input layer, one hidden layer along with an dropout layer and one output layer has been implemented

Calculate the prevalence of the positive class : Prevalence is the proportion of a population who are positive to autism spectrum disorder in a given time period.

In [10]:
def calc_prevalence(target):
    # this function calculates the prevalence of the positive class (label = 1)
    return sum(target) / len(target)


print(
    "prevalence of the positive class: %.3f"
    % calc_prevalence(data["target"].values)
)

prevalence of the positive class: 0.498

# splitting data into positive and negative cases
rows_pos = data.target == 1
df_train_pos = data.loc[rows_pos]
df_train_neg = data.loc[~rows_pos]

# len(df_train_pos) = 397
# len(df_train_neg) = 400
n = np.min([len(df_train_pos), len(df_train_neg)])

# merge the balanced data
df_train = pd.concat([df_train_pos.sample(n=n, random_state=69), df_train_neg.sample(n=n, random_state=69)], axis=0, ignore_index=True)

# shuffle the order of the training sample
# df_train = df_train.sample(n=len(df_train), random_state=69).reset_index(drop=True)

print('Train balanced prevalence(n = %d):%.3f'%(len(df_train), calc_prevalence(df_train.target.values)))

PCA for dimensionality reduction¶

Using dimension reduction, we can approximate the original dataset with fewer variables, while reducing computational power to run our model. Using PCA, we can study the cumulative explained variance ratio of these features to understand which features explain the most variance in the data.

In [14]:

X_valid = pca.transform(X_valid)
explained_variance = pca.explained_variance_ratio_

Model Selection¶

Print all our model metrics with one function print_report()

In [18]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score, accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score

def calc_specificity(y_actual, y_pred, thresh):
    # calculates specificity
    return sum((y_pred < thresh) & (y_actual == 0)) /sum(y_actual ==0)

def print_report(y_actual, y_pred, thresh):
    
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_actual, (y_pred > thresh))
    recall = recall_score(y_actual, (y_pred > thresh))
    precision = precision_score(y_actual, (y_pred > thresh))
    specificity = calc_specificity(y_actual, y_pred, thresh)
    print('AUC:%.3f'%auc)
    print('accuracy:%.3f'%accuracy)
    print('recall:%.3f'%recall)
    print('precision:%.3f'%precision)
    print('specificity:%.3f'%specificity)
    print('prevalence:%.3f'%calc_prevalence(y_actual))
    print(' ')
    return auc, accuracy, recall, precision, specificity

import time

my_params =  np.arange(0.05, 1.01, 0.05) # fill this in your list of parameters

# initialize arrays for storing the results
train_metrics = np.zeros(len(my_params))
valid_metrics = np.zeros(len(my_params))

# train a model for each param in a list
t1 = time.time()
for jj in range(len(my_params)):
    my_param = my_params[jj]
    
    # fit model
    model = ExtraTreesClassifier(bootstrap=False, criterion="entropy", max_features=my_param, min_samples_leaf=3, min_samples_split=20, n_estimators=100)
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # get predictions
    y_train_preds = model.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1]
    y_valid_preds = model.predict_proba(X_valid)[:,1]

    # calculate auc
    metric_train = roc_auc_score(y_train, y_train_preds) # fill this in
    metric_valid = roc_auc_score(y_valid, y_valid_preds) # fill this in

    # save aucs
    train_metrics[jj] = metric_train
    valid_metrics[jj] = metric_valid
    
    # print the time
    t2 = time.time()
    print(my_param, t2-t1)
    t1 = time.time()

import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import learning_curve
from sklearn.model_selection import ShuffleSplit
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_learning_curve(estimator, title, X, y, ylim=None, cv=None,
                        n_jobs=1, train_sizes=np.linspace(.1, 1.0, 5)):
    """
    Generate a simple plot of the test and training learning curve.

    Parameters
    ----------
    estimator : object type that implements the "fit" and "predict" methods
        An object of that type which is cloned for each validation.

    title : string
        Title for the chart.

    X : array-like, shape (n_samples, n_features)
        Training vector, where n_samples is the number of samples and
        n_features is the number of features.

    y : array-like, shape (n_samples) or (n_samples, n_features), optional
        Target relative to X for classification or regression;
        None for unsupervised learning.

    ylim : tuple, shape (ymin, ymax), optional
        Defines minimum and maximum yvalues plotted.

    cv : int, cross-validation generator or an iterable, optional
        Determines the cross-validation splitting strategy.
        Possible inputs for cv are:
          - None, to use the default 3-fold cross-validation,
          - integer, to specify the number of folds.
          - An object to be used as a cross-validation generator.
          - An iterable yielding train/test splits.

        For integer/None inputs, if ``y`` is binary or multiclass,
        :class:`StratifiedKFold` used. If the estimator is not a classifier
        or if ``y`` is neither binary nor multiclass, :class:`KFold` is used.

        Refer :ref:`User Guide <cross_validation>` for the various
        cross-validators that can be used here.

    n_jobs : integer, optional
        Number of jobs to run in parallel (default 1).
    """
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
    plt.title(title)
    if ylim is not None:
        plt.ylim(*ylim)
    plt.xlabel("Training examples")
    plt.ylabel("AUC")
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(
        estimator, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes, scoring = 'roc_auc')
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    plt.grid()

    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,
                     train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,
                     color="r")
    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,
                     test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="b")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r",
             label="Training score")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="b",
             label="Cross-validation score")

    plt.legend(loc="best")
    return plt

def create_larger():
    # create model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(64,input_dim=46,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.1))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model
estimators = []
estimators.append(('standardize', StandardScaler()))
